<biogHist>
<abstract>Mandatory reporting is a legal requirement that some professional groups or volunteers report child abuse.</abstract>
<p>Mandatory reporting was first introduced by the <span style="font-style:italic">Child Protection Act</span> (1974). It required that professions designated by the Governor had to report any suspected cases of child abuse. In 2013, mandatory reporting continues under the <span style="font-style:italic">Children, Young Persons and their Families Act</span> (1997) which requires the following people to report suspected child abuse:</p>
<list><item>Medical practitioners, dentists, psychologists and nurses.</item>
<item>Teachers, school principals, kindergarten teachers, and child care workers.</item>
<item>Law enforcement officers and probation officers.</item>
<item>Child welfare officers.</item>
<item>Managers of a child care service.</item>
<item>People employed by, or volunteering in, government agencies or organisations that provide health, welfare, education, residential services or care wholly or partly for children and are funded by the Crown.</item></list>

</biogHist>
